Want to participate in some historic bargain hunting in Tokyo? 

The Setagaya Boroichi (Setagaya Flea Market) first took place in 1578 (wow!). It got its start as a market selling fabric scraps (or âBoroâ, in Japanese). 

While you can see find numerous secondhand kimono and fabric stalls today, youâll also be treated to vendors selling everything from tools to toys, as well as food, furniture and even plants. And unlike most shopping experiences in Japan, you can even practice a little bargaining here. 

ð The Setagaya Boroichi takes place annual on December 15-16, and again on January 15-16.

ðStalls line the streets between Kamimachi and Setagaya stations on the Setagaya Tram line. 

All video taken at the Setagaya Boroichi in Dec 2022.
